<li><cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFFisher1992">Fisher, Nick (1992). <i>Hybris: a study in the values of honour and shame in Ancient Greece</i>. <a href="/wiki/Warminster" title="Warminster">Warminster</a>, UK: Aris &amp; Phillips.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Hybris%3A+a+study+in+the+values+of+honour+and+shame+in+Ancient+Greece&amp;rft.aulast=Fisher&amp;rft.aufirst=Nick&amp;rft.au=Fisher%2C+Nick&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft.place=%5B%5BWarminster%5D%5D%2C+UK&amp;rft.pub=Aris+%26+Phillips&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Hubris"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span> A book-length discussion of the meaning and implications of hybristic behavior in ancient Greece.</li>
<li>MacDowell, Douglas. "<i>Hybris</i> in Athens." <i>Greece and Rome</i> 23 (1976) 14-31.</li>
<li>Owen, David (2007) <a href="http://www.politicospublishing.co.uk/titles.php/itemcode/178" class="external text" title="http://www.politicospublishing.co.uk/titles.php/itemcode/178" rel="nofollow"><i>The Hubris Syndrome: Bush, Blair and the Intoxication of Power</i></a> Politico's, Methuen Publishing Ltd.</li>
</ul>
